"That's gonna do it for me, friends. I'll be back soon. Next up is all classics all hour, and remember — I'll never leave you, because I'm always here."

"Wake up," he muttered, stretching as he reached over and changed the station. "Let's hear some news."

"—corn's trading at two-sixty a bushel, beans around five-eighty, winter wheat holding at three-forty on the board this morning. Suet steady. Blood meal up slightly. Human flesh down a touch on the week. Rounding out the morning report, hog futures unchanged, cotton holding firm."

David looked at the cloud-covered sky, trees blurring past the edge of his sight as the voice moved on to the weather.

"—expect clear skies through the morning hours, temperatures climbing to one-forty-seven by early afternoon across the region, dropping to near ninety by evening."

David stared at the radio so long the car drifted. He grabbed the wheel, breath snagging with it.

He shook his head and sat up straight.

"What the hell?" he said to no one.

The tone shifted, warmer now.

"—tickets are moving fast this year, organizers say, so don't wait if you want a seat for the skinning."

David's hand stopped on the volume knob.

"—and don't forget, the Ladies' Auxiliary potluck moves to Thursday this week, same time, same place, bring a covered dish. Founders Day parade lineup's posted down at the co-op."

He sighed, shoulders dropping an inch.

"Skinning," he said.

He turned the volume up instead of down.

The droning kept on, voice and music both blurring into the same flat hum. He caught himself somewhere past that, jaw slack, eyes open but pointed at nothing in particular.

"Music didn't work," Dave muttered. "News sucks too."

He reached toward the passenger seat without looking, patting around for a drink, a snack, anything. No drink in the cup holder. No snacks in the seat.

"Where's my—" He stopped himself, hand going still on the empty seat. The question sat there a second before the real one came. "When'd I stop last?"

He couldn't say. Dave didn't remember the last time he'd driven past a gas station, or the last time he'd seen another car.

He didn't know where he was going. Worse: he didn't know where he'd come from. He got lost in thought, chasing it for something solid, and there wasn't anything solid. That's when he realized his foot had already come off the gas.

He caught his own eyes in the rearview mirror and held there a second too long. That's when he noticed the orange starting to gather behind him, low along the treeline like something catching fire.

He eased off further, and the light didn't wait for David. It came on faster than he was slowing, spreading along both sides of the road now, and he could see it was flame, like a wildfire climbing the treeline on both sides.

The crackling of the trees came in under the engine noise, then a low roar under that. He could feel the heat on his face, radiating through the glass.

He put his foot down. Hard. The engine kicked, inertia shoving him back into the seat as the car surged forward. The glow shrank in the rearview mirror, dimmer with every second he put between himself and the flames.

David took a few quick breaths and looked around. His hands found the wheel again, tighter than before.

"What the hell," he said, quiet. He looked around once more. "What the hell is going on?"

He started changing the stations, one after another.

A weather report, normal enough, cut off before it finished. A commercial jingle, upbeat, selling something he couldn't place. A preacher's voice, cadence rising and falling, words blurring past too fast to catch. One station was just breathing, slow and even, close to the mic. Another might have been laughing, if laughing could sound like that.

He kept going, faster now.

The next one had no noise in it at all. Not static. Not silence with something underneath, waiting. Just clean, dead quiet, the kind that meant the radio was working and nothing at all was coming through it.

He hit the next station. Nothing. The next. Nothing. Every station, the same flawless quiet.

Dave drove on in silence, lost in thought, his heartbeat climbing without him deciding it should. No other cars. No side roads breaking off from this one. He didn't know where he was going, and he still didn't know where he'd come from.

He looked down for the gas gauge instead. Everything else on the dash was right where it should be — the speed, the RPMs, all of it lit and working. He looked again, slower this time, sure he was just missing it. There was nowhere for his eyes to land. It wasn't broken, wasn't blank. It simply wasn't there, like the panel had never had one to begin with.

"What the hell is going on?" Dave said. "Am I dreaming? This isn't—" He stopped. "This isn't real. What the hell?"

Then, so quiet he almost missed it under the hum, a voice from the radio. A woman's voice, soft, almost gentle.

"This isn't real."

The radio settled back into its low, empty hum, like it had never spoken at all.

Dave stared at the radio, lost in shock.

The car began to drift, slow at first, off the road. He didn't feel it happen. By the time he noticed, he was already crossing onto the shoulder, and that's when the light came back — orange, low, gathering at the treeline like it had been waiting for exactly this.

Dave's attention snapped back to the road. For half a second, testing it, he let the car drift further instead of correcting. The flames answered instantly. Not creeping now, but rushing the car like they'd been given permission, close enough that he nearly lost the wheel wrenching himself back onto the road. "What the actual fuck is going on?"

He turned on the inside light, frantically searching with one hand for his phone.

"Hey, Dave. You're not gonna find your phone."

The voice sounded too familiar. Dave knew it before he let himself know it. A lifelong friend, Stephen. Stephen's voice, right there on the radio like it belonged.

He stopped mid-search, hand frozen against the seat, staring at the radio.

"No. No. No. No. No. No."

"Yes, Dave." Stephen's voice, calm, right back at him.

"This doesn't make sense," Dave said. "This is impossible."

"And yet you're here," Stephen said, a bit of sadness in his voice.

"Dude, what the hell is going on!" Dave's voice was higher, loud and shrill. "Are you fucking with me? How are you doing all this? How are you talking to me?"

Dave drove in silence, staring at the radio, waiting for an answer.

"What the fuck. Answer me. Talk to me." His voice climbed further. "Why are you doing this to me? Why are you fucking with me?"

"Come on, man," Stephen said. "You know me. You know this really isn't me. Just keep driving, Dave."

"Keep driving? Keep driving where? Where am I going? What's going on? What happened? Where are you? Is there a wildfire?"

"This isn't me, Dave. You know this isn't me."

"What do you mean this isn't you? I'm talking to you. I have no idea what's happening."

No answer came. The radio's hum and the engine under it blurred together as the car kept on.

"Hello?" Dave said. "Stephen? Dude?"

His foot had come off the gas again, and the orange light was already crawling back — behind him first, then along both sides. "Oh, shit." He slammed the pedal down, the car lurching forward.

"This can't be real. This has to be a nightmare. This can't be real."

The radio began changing stations on its own, cycling fast, and what came through wasn't static or music anymore. It was voices. His own, younger, caught in the middle of a replay of an embarrassing moment from childhood. Then another clip, another conversation. Then a different voice — a friend, telling Dave about some situation, some thought he'd had, something he never said out loud himself.
